Ultimately, better fire prediction could have significant benefits for those currently trying to fight, manage and coexist with fire.
Nevertheless, the link between atmospheric dryness and forest fire risk in many regions means we should be able to develop better fire predictions, at both seasonal and near-term scales.
It‚Äôs important to note that VPD is not the be all and end all, and there are many regions and forest types where vapour pressure deficit is not the main driver of fire.

We can also expect increasing human health impacts from wildfire smoke. Over 330,000 annual deaths globally are attributable to smoke inhalation, a number that could increase notably by the turn of the century https://t.co/Ag5Z2KHoNo

Increasing forest fires will have serious implications for carbon storage in those regions and potentially the global carbon cycle. It was recently reported that the role of the Amazon as a carbon sink may already be in decline. https://t.co/w9An5qjAXV
Some of the biggest areas of concern are the Amazon rainforest and other tropical forests, as well as northern hemisphere temperate and boreal forests.
We looked at both low and high emissions scenarios and found the risks are much greater if we fail to curb emissions.

Unfortunately, we found that without strong climate action, there will be many more days each year when many of the Earth‚Äôs forests cross over into this highly flammable state. This means we‚Äôre likely to see more major fires, with all the risks that come with them.

Our results show that in many regions, forest fire is much more likely above a certain threshold in vapour pressure deficit. This threshold was lower in boreal and temperate forests and higher in Mediterranean, subtropical and tropical forests.

We found that in all kinds of forests around the world, from temperate eucalypt forests to boreal coniferous forests and tropical rainforests, there is a strong link between fire activity and how thirsty the air is at a daily timescale.
We tested this link between VPD and fires on a global scale, looking at daily climate and forest fire records over the last 20yr or so
Importantly, warmer air can hold more water, which means vapour pressure deficit (VPD) increases - and fuels can dry out more often - with rising temps due to climate change.

@NussbaumAbigail Anyone with a passing familiarity with how succession proceeded in the Ottoman Empire might find the notion of billionaires each having dozens of offspring the beginning of a very interesting set of stories best viewed from a safe distance

A good rule of thumb, when listening to someone who thinks that they can reshape the future, is to ask "does this person seem to understand that theirs is not the only valid life experience". A lot of our modern techbro elites don't pass that test.

It's not surprising that this class of billionaires are also dipping their toes in eugenics, scientific racism, and queerphobia. These are all natural offshoots of believing yourself to be the only type of person who counts, and who should embody the future of humanity.

(Obviously, most of these people are not really like Musk, and he doesn't consider them his equals. But the fantasy he's selling is that they could one day be him, and thus earn a place in the future that he's reserving only for their kind.)

But I also see hints of it in how Musk has been steadily worsening working conditions at Twitter. All his policies seem designed to weed out people of color, women, parents, the disabled. Anyone who isn't a young, healthy workaholic willing to give their life to the company.

You see this, also, in the recently-reported pro-natalism of the billionaire class. Again, when longtermists say that there should be more humans, what they mean is humans like them. For some of them, that means having dozens of genetic offsprings.https://t.co/YajSPOu3qj

"People like us" doesn't have to mean white (though it often does), but it does mean sharing similar class and cultural markers. The future that longtermism envisions reduces humanity to a monoculture, because those are the only humans that matter to its adherents.

(It should go without saying, but the proposed trade-off is a fantasy. There is no future in which the Global South becomes uninhabitable, but the Global North - or even small parts of it - carries on as normal. It would be an apocalypse for all of us.)

The supposed justification for this trade-off is that these enclaves will eventually produce the technological breakthroughs that will take humanity to the stars. But that word, "humanity", is concealing some very ugly ideas about who gets to live in that future.

As the article makes clear, longtermism is a way of putting a benevolent gloss on "we don't care if billions of people from the Global South die so long as people like us can maintain the same technological, affluent lifestyle, if only in small enclaves."

@ChloBrim Regarding policy, I hope policymakers do not use a single article written to argue for the importance of heating homes to make decisions about, say, cooling centers in cities.Policies generally happen at different scales than what total deaths by hazard per year would indicate.

@ChloBrim Scientific studies have context that is difficult to know without training in that field. Writing for a wider audience has generally not been the goal.This is changing with #openaccess, but I am concerned this has been pushed by publishers to increase profit.

@TC_Chakraborty I think we've learnt we agree but this is a complicated area that doesn't fit in a tweet! I'm going to think about how I change how I communicate cold Vs heat deaths to better capture the complexity.

@TC_Chakraborty But would you agree. Maybe someone needs to do a study or something because it's not a like for like comparison? Maybe we are actually just confusing people outside this field. And how does that translate to policy action?

@ChloBrim Climate change is expected to reduce cold deaths and increase heat deaths. But climate change is more than just temperature-related deaths. Our existing infrastructure is designed for the current climate regime and changes in that regime will have major impacts across sectors.
@ChloBrim Climate deniers are gonna climate change deny. If cold deaths are not compared to heat deaths (but are to other weather hazards), their argument will be that there is a clear media bias.

@TC_Chakraborty Because climate deniers use it to say the #climatechange is a good thing. If am article focuses on cold adaptation isn't cold deaths enough most people have no idea about extreme temperature deaths. Why do you need heat? It's just confusing things.
